  "estimatedMinutes": 35,
  "concept": "Numbers come up constantly — prices, ages, phone numbers, times — so they're worth drilling cold.\n\n0–16 are single words to memorise: zéro, un, deux … seize. (un also means \"a/an\", with a feminine une.) Then 17–19 turn logical: dix-sept, dix-huit, dix-neuf (\"ten-seven…\").\n\nThe tens are vingt (20), trente (30), quarante (40), cinquante (50), soixante (60). Build the numbers in between with a hyphen — vingt-trois (23), trente-cinq (35) — and slip in \"et\" for 21/31/41…: vingt-et-un, trente-et-un.\n\nNow the famous French quirk, from 70 up: French goes base-20 (counting in twenties).\n  • 70 = soixante-dix, literally \"sixty-ten\". Keep adding: 71 = soixante et onze, 72 = soixante-douze … 79 = soixante-dix-neuf.\n  • 80 = quatre-vingts, literally \"four-twenties\" (4 × 20). Then 81 = quatre-vingt-un, 82 = quatre-vingt-deux … (quatre-vingts drops its -s as soon as another number follows).\n  • 90 = quatre-vingt-dix, \"four-twenties-ten\". Then 91 = quatre-vingt-onze … 99 = quatre-vingt-dix-neuf.\nIt feels odd at first, but it's just arithmetic out loud. (Belgium and Switzerland use the tidier septante / huitante / nonante — but France uses the base-20 forms, so those are the ones to learn.)\n\nPractise saying them out of order — prices and phone numbers never arrive politely counting upward. Use the audio buttons and notice the rhythm.\n\nSay your age, a phone number, and three prices out loud — you'll hit the 70–99 forms fast.",
